Predicting GDP per capita¶

Introduction:

This is an exploratory data analysis (EDA) of the Countries of the World dataset found on Kaggle at: https://www.kaggle.com/fernandol/countries-of-the-world. The goal is to better understand the dataset by exploring key relationships between variables through visualization, focusing specifically on GDP per capita. It concludes with constructing, and improving multiple linear regression models, as well as creating a random forest regression model to predict GDP per capita.

There are 17 categorical variables and 3 numeric variables (including the target variable, GDP per capita). However, many of these (such as population density, coastline, net migration, infant mortality per 1000 births, literacy rate, phones per 1000 people, arable percentage, crops percentage, other percentage, birthrate, deathrate, agriculture, industry, and service) will need to be converted to the appropriate numeric data types. Climate is a categorical variable represented by numeric values currently in string format.

There are a handful of missing values for many of the various attributes. These will be replaced by the average value of each variable for the region which that country belongs to.

Replace missing data with the mean value of the variable by region:

Since the average values of the region that each country belongs to are going to be more representative of the missing attribute values in this dataset than simply taking the averge of the entire dataset for variables with missing data, the below calculations were run in order to replace missing values with the most appropriate estimate/approximation. The mode was used to estimate missing values for the climate variable, as it is actually categorical in nature.

In [7]:
for col in data.columns.values:
    if data[col].isnull().sum() == 0:
        continue
    if col == 'climate':
        estimate = data.groupby('region')['climate'].apply(lambda x: x.mode().max())
    else:
        estimate = data.groupby('region')[col].median()
    for region in data['region'].unique():
        data[col].loc[(data[col].isnull()) & (data['region'] == region)] = estimate[region]

The above correlation matrix heatmap shows the correlations between all numerical variables in the dataset. Most of the correlations that are going to be of greatest interest are those relating to GDP per capita. For instance, there is an 83% correlation between GDP per capita and phones (# per 1000 ppl), indicating that wealthier societies have more citizens with phones. Another point of interest/concern, is the fact that there is an 84% correlation between birth rate and infant mortality, indicating possible multicollinearity. One of these variables will most likely need to be removed (along with the variable other, which has a -86% correlation with arable) from the dataset before attempting any regression modeling.

Scatter plots of nine variables with highest correlations (absolute value) to GDP per capita:

In [18]:
sns.set(style = 'darkgrid')
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows = 3, ncols = 3, figsize = (20,20))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace = 0.3, wspace = 0.2)

color = ['r','orange', 'b', 'y', 'grey', 'g', 'brown', 'purple', 'black']
header = ['GDP vs Phones', 'GDP vs Birth Rate', 'GDP vs Infant Mortality', 'GDP vs Agriculture', 
          'GDP vs Service', 'GDP vs Literacy', 'GDP vs Migration', 'GDP vs Crops', 'GDP vs Death Rate']

# Determine highest correlations
gdp_corr = pd.Series()
for col in data.columns.values[2:]:
    if ((col != 'gdp') & (col != 'climate')):
        gdp_corr[col] = data['gdp'].corr(data[col])
corr_abs = gdp_corr.abs().sort_values(ascending = False)
gdp_corr = gdp_corr.loc[corr_abs.index]

count = 0
for i in range(3):
    for j in range(3):
        sns.regplot(x = gdp_corr.index.values[i*3+j], y ='gdp', data = data,
                   ax = axes[i,j], fit_reg = False, marker ='.', color = color[count])
        title = header[count]
        axes[i,j].set_title(title)
        count += 1
axes[1,2].set_xlim(0,102)
plt.show()

The above scatter plots visually portray the correlations between GDP per capita and the nine attributes (phones, birth rate, infant mortality, agriculture, service, literacy, migration, crops, and death rate) that displayed the highest correlations (in terms of absolute value) in the prior correlation matrix. From this, it is apparent that phones (# per 1000 ppl) has a strong, positive relationship with GDP per capita. Alternatively, there is a relatively strong, negative relationship between birth rate and GDP per capita. The relationship between the rest of the variables graphed above and GDP per capita can be interpreted in a similar manner.

2. Data Modeling¶

Split data into training and test sets:

In [19]:
# Manually encode region variable to numeric values
region_num = {'SUB-SAHARAN AFRICA': 1, 'LATIN AMER. & CARIB': 2, 'WESTERN EUROPE': 3, 'ASIA (EX. NEAR EAST)': 4,
              'OCEANIA': 5, 'NEAR EAST': 6, 'EASTERN EUROPE': 7, 'C.W. OF IND. STATES': 8, 'NORTHERN AFRICA': 9,
              'NORTHERN AMERICA': 10, 'BALTICS': 11}

data = data.replace(region_num)

# Split data into training and test sets
train, test = train_test_split(data, test_size = 0.3, shuffle = True, random_state = 40)

# Include all attributes except birth rate & other (multicollinearity concerns)
training_attributes = ['region', 'population', 'area', 'density', 'coastline', 'migration', 'infant mortality',

Removing the attributes of least importance did improve the second model slightly, with a small reduction in the root mean square error (rmse) in the test set and a slight increase in the R-squared value in the test set. The root mean square error (rmse) of the test set is now 5,819.7, and the R-squared value of the test set is 70.0, indicating that this model now explains about 70% of the variability in GDP per capita.

However, the model could be futher improved by normalizing the distribution of GDP per capita by transforming it to the log of GDP per capita. This will effectively give more weight to countries with lower GDP levels, and reduce the impact of outliers with extremely high economic output.

Transform GDP per capita to the log of GDP per capita:

In [26]:
train_y = train_y.to_frame()

train_y = train_y['gdp']

test_y = test_y.to_frame()
test_y['gdp'] = np.log(test_y['gdp'])
test_y = test_y['gdp']

Bar plot of feature importance:

In [34]:
# Function to plot feature importance

def feature_importance_plot(importance, names, model_type):

    feature_importance = np.array(importance)
    feature_names = np.array(names)


    data={'feature_names':feature_names,'feature_importance':feature_importance}
    feat_import_df = pd.DataFrame(data)

    feat_import_df.sort_values(by=['feature_importance'], ascending=False, inplace=True)


    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    sns.barplot(x=feat_import_df['feature_importance'], y=feat_import_df['feature_names'])
    plt.title(model_type + ' Feature Importance', fontsize=15)
    plt.xlabel('Feature Importance')
    plt.ylabel('Features')
In [35]:
feature_importance_plot(model4.feature_importances_, train_x.columns, 'Random Forest Model')

The above bar plot of the importance of each attribute in the random forest regression model shows that the three most significant features in predicting (normalized) GDP per capita are phones (# per 1000 ppl), followed by infant mortality (# per 1000 births), and agriculture (% of economy). Literacy rate also appears to be a somewhat important factor. However, it seems that the primary indicator of a country's economic output per person is based on the extent to which its citizens are connected via phones.
